### Column Layouts

If you want to preserve every photo's full composition without cropping and use the space efficiently, CSS columns layout is one of the options. It uses fixed column widths so images keep their intrinsic aspect ratios while the columns create vertical stacks.

![Column-based layout](./assets/columns.svg "Column layout — portrait photos dominate visually")

Here's a minimal implementation:

```css
/* Baseline: CSS multi-column layout */
.gallery {
  columns: 3;
  column-gap: 1rem;
}

.gallery img {
  width: 100%;
  margin-bottom: 1rem;
}
```

Columns layout is attractive because it preserves composition, has minimal wasted space, and feels less rigid than strict cells. It, however, has a few practical implications you should be aware of when choosing a gallery strategy:

1) Portraits dominate visually.  
Taller images occupy more vertical space than wide ones, so a single portrait can outweigh two landscapes beside it. That imbalance makes portrait-heavy collections read as visually dominant.

![Unsplash — column layout](https://share.kadykov.com/images/blog/designing-a-photo-gallery-layout/unsplash-columns.avif "Unsplash's column layout — portrait shots on the sides visually dominate the landscapes in the center column")

2) Rhythm is directional.  
Consistent column widths produce strong vertical leading lines repeated horizontally. That directional rhythm is not inherently a flaw — it is a characteristic you can lean into or soften by adjusting the gap size. For galleries that prioritize portraits, the unidirectional rhythm can be an asset: it reinforces the prominence of tall images and helps guide the eye down columns.

![Column layout with leading lines](./assets/columns-leading-lines.svg "Vertical leading lines are strong — horizontal gaps are scattered, forming no lines")

3) Fill order is counterintuitive.  
By default multi-column layout fills top-to-bottom, then left-to-right (like text). For long galleries this can hide recently added photos below the fold — viewers often expect the newest items to appear first across the top row, not stacked down the first column.

![CSS column fill order](./assets/columns-CSS-order.svg "Filling inherited from text: complete the first column before moving to the next one")

![CSS column order with long gallery](./assets/columns-CSS-order-long.svg "CSS-only filling hides photos 3-4 and 7-8 below the fold")

Fixing the fill order requires JavaScript: reorder or position items so the layout fills left-to-right row by row instead of the browser's default text-like flow.

![Natural fill order](./assets/columns-natural-order.svg "Natural fill order: left-to-right, top-to-bottom, requires JS to implement")

In short: the columns layout preserves full images and feels organic. Portrait dominance and a pronounced directional rhythm are natural outcomes — not defects — and can be used deliberately (or tuned via gap size and composition choices). The fill-order quirk is the main practical downside to address if you want a traditional left‑to‑right browsing sequence.
 
