## The Result

Here's how the layout works in practice. The cell-span grid handles mixed orientations naturally—portrait shots of street scenes sit alongside wide mountain landscapes, and neither dominates visually. Polaroid borders frame each image consistently, and the slight rotation gives the page a tactile, handmade quality.

![Photo gallery on kadykov.com](https://share.kadykov.com/images/blog/designing-a-photo-gallery-layout/cell-span.avif "The cell-span layout with Polaroid borders and slight rotation")

You can explore the full implementation at [kadykov.com/photos](/photos) or the [source code](https://github.com/kadykov/kadykov.com).

The layout's effectiveness becomes clearer when you examine it with browser DevTools. The underlying grid reveals both the structure and the cost: some cells remain trapped between photo spans, others sit unused at row ends. This is the visual price of equal presentation—space efficiency traded for balanced weight across orientations.

![Real grid overlay in browser](https://share.kadykov.com/images/blog/designing-a-photo-gallery-layout/cell-span-grid.avif "DevTools reveals the grid — notice the trapped cell on the left and unused cells on the right")

One final detail completes the viewing environment: the page uses a **neutral gray background** with zero chroma. This prevents any hue bias from affecting color perception—unlike warm beige or cool blue-grays, true neutral gray doesn't push reds, greens, or blues in any direction. Combined with the off-white Polaroid borders, this creates a consistent viewing context that works equally well in light and dark modes. The result is closer to a color-neutral print viewing environment than the stark white or deep black backgrounds common on photo sites.

The wasted space is noticeable if you look for it, but in practice it reads as intentional—part of the design rather than a layout bug. Because gaps don't align into strong leading lines, the empty cells feel like natural breathing room rather than obvious inefficiency. For a navigational gallery where the goal is equal browsing weight, not maximum density, that trade-off makes sense.

